That and I'd have liked a little more information storywise, because plenty of that was also missing and going in blind on the mobile version makes the story seem a bit confusing. The clips from at home with the popcorn and t.v. aren't included, which is a shame. I guess all in all I prefer the PC version, but the mobile version is still a engaging play with amazing graphics and fun gameplay. A very good app to pass time, although maybe not if you want the full experience. 4/5 stars, great work, Scott.

I never wanted to say so, but this series has finally lost its way...would have much rather seen them go out on FNAF 4, which wasn't perfect but was a big return to form after the flop of #3. Anyway, this one departs from the format pretty drastically and is a series of mini-games loosely tied together with a story. The story and the ending it leads you to are definitely kind of fun, but worth your time and energy? Probably not. Mostly because the long 1-2 minute intro voiceover sequences for each night (as well as all the meaningless tunnel crawling) are AGONIZING upon repeat play. The jokes don't even change...I mean, the "Casual Bongos" thing was kind of funny, but not by the twelfth time. Even the menu screen on this game is impossibly slow. If you don't finish the whole thing in one sitting, you will be punished for it. I think the best thing that can be said for "Sister Location" is that it made me appreciate the simple, genius gameplay of the first FNAF like never before.

The mobile port of Sister Location is good. I'm not sure why Scott decided to cut a big bulk of content (some of which i thought necessary), but it still comes out OK. The audio loops are buggy and sound effects are cut down drastically in some parts of the game, making some sections feel awkward. Custom Night becomes much harder due to audio glitches, and other various bugs. If Scott adds in the rest of the missing content and does some muchneeded bug fixing, this would be a near perfect port of the PC version - which I prefer over this one. Still a damn good game and port, and very fun despite its shortcomings.
